<!-- 3: GRAMMAR -->
<!-- SECTION: Grammar Focus -->
<section id="grammar" class="c3">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">3</span>Grammar Focus</h2>

  <h3 style="color:var(--blue);">3.1 — Present Simple: Form</h3>
  <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
    <tr><th>Subject</th><th>Form</th><th>Example</th></tr>
    <tr><td>I / you / we / they</td><td>base verb</td><td>I <b>wake up</b> at 6:30.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>he / she / it</td><td>verb <b>+ s</b></td><td>She <b>walks</b> to school.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>negative (I/you/we/they)</td><td><b>don't</b> + verb</td><td>We <b>don't skip</b> breakfast.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>negative (he/she/it)</td><td><b>doesn't</b> + verb</td><td>He <b>doesn't finish</b> early.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>question</td><td><b>Do/Does</b> + subject + verb?</td><td><b>Does</b> she <b>walk</b> to school?</td></tr>
  </table></div>
  <p>We use the present simple for routines, habits, and things that are always or usually true — exactly what Sofia uses to describe her normal day.</p>

  <div class="error-box">
    <h4>⚠️ Don't Forget the "-s"!</h4>
    <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
      <tr><th>❌ Incorrect</th><th>✅ Correct</th></tr>
      <tr><td>She wake up at 6:30.</td><td>She <b>wakes</b> up at 6:30.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>He don't like coffee.</td><td>He <b>doesn't</b> like coffee.</td></tr>
    </table></div>
    <p style="margin-bottom:0;">Only <b>he / she / it</b> need the extra "-s" on the verb — and in negatives, "doesn't" already has the "-s", so the main verb goes back to normal: "He <b>doesn't like</b>" (NOT "doesn't likes").</p>
  </div>

  <div class="ccq-box">
    <h4>🔎 Check Your Understanding</h4>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Does Sofia wake up at 6:30 just today, or every day?</b> <span>Every day — it's her routine.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Do we add "-s" for "I"?</b> <span>No.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Do we add "-s" for "she"?</b> <span>Yes — "she wakes up".</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Is "He doesn't likes coffee" correct?</b> <span>No — after "doesn't", the verb has no "-s": "He doesn't like coffee".</span></div>
  </div>

  <h3 style="color:var(--blue);">3.2 — Possessive Adjectives</h3>
  <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
    <tr><th>Subject</th><th>Possessive adjective</th><th>Example</th></tr>
    <tr><td>I</td><td><b>my</b></td><td><b>My</b> husband is called Mark.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>you</td><td><b>your</b></td><td>Is this <b>your</b> family?</td></tr>
    <tr><td>he</td><td><b>his</b></td><td>Leo goes with <b>his</b> grandmother.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>she</td><td><b>her</b></td><td>Emma walks with <b>her</b> friend.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>it</td><td><b>its</b></td><td>The building has <b>its</b> own garden.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>we</td><td><b>our</b></td><td><b>Our</b> daughter is 8 years old.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>they</td><td><b>their</b></td><td>Emma and Leo love <b>their</b> grandmother.</td></tr>
  </table></div>
  <p style="font-size:14px;">Remember: "his" is for a man, "her" is for a woman — this doesn't match the noun after it, only the person the word belongs to.</p>

  <div class="ccq-box">
    <h4>🔎 Check Your Understanding</h4>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Is "his" for a man or a woman?</b> <span>A man.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Emma has a friend. Do we say "her friend" or "his friend"?</b> <span>Her friend — Emma is a girl.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Sofia and Mark have a daughter. Do we say "my daughter" or "their daughter"?</b> <span>Their daughter — it belongs to both of them.</span></div>
  </div>

  <h3 style="color:var(--blue);">3.3 — Adverbs of Frequency</h3>
  <p>These words say <b>how often</b> something happens. They go in a special position — before the main verb, but after the verb "be".</p>

  <div class="tl-diagram">
    <div class="tl-diagram-title">The frequency scale: 100% → 0%</div>
    <svg viewBox="0 0 660 150" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
      <rect x="30" y="65" width="600" height="16" rx="8" fill="url(#freqgrad)"/>
      <defs>
        <linearGradient id="freqgrad" x1="0" y1="0" x2="1" y2="0">
          <stop offset="0%" stop-color="#5b4636"/>
          <stop offset="100%" stop-color="#e0d7ca"/>
        </linearGradient>
      </defs>
      <circle cx="60" cy="73" r="9" fill="#5b4636" stroke="#fff" stroke-width="2"/>
      <text x="60" y="45" font-size="14" fill="#5b4636" font-family="Calibri" font-weight="bold" text-anchor="middle">always</text>
      <text x="60" y="105" font-size="12" fill="#5c5346" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">100%</text>
      <circle cx="240" cy="73" r="9" fill="#7d5ba6" stroke="#fff" stroke-width="2"/>
      <text x="240" y="45" font-size="14" fill="#7d5ba6" font-family="Calibri" font-weight="bold" text-anchor="middle">usually</text>
      <text x="240" y="105" font-size="12" fill="#5c5346" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">~80%</text>
      <circle cx="420" cy="73" r="9" fill="#4a6fa5" stroke="#fff" stroke-width="2"/>
      <text x="420" y="45" font-size="14" fill="#4a6fa5" font-family="Calibri" font-weight="bold" text-anchor="middle">sometimes</text>
      <text x="420" y="105" font-size="12" fill="#5c5346" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">~40%</text>
      <circle cx="600" cy="73" r="9" fill="#b0a89a" stroke="#fff" stroke-width="2"/>
      <text x="600" y="45" font-size="14" fill="#8c8478" font-family="Calibri" font-weight="bold" text-anchor="middle">never</text>
      <text x="600" y="105" font-size="12" fill="#5c5346" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">0%</text>
      <text x="330" y="135" font-size="12.5" fill="#5c5346" font-family="Calibri" font-style="italic" text-anchor="middle">Learners often overuse "always" and "never" — try "usually" and "sometimes" too!</text>
    </svg>
    <div class="tl-caption">Real English uses "usually" and "sometimes" much more often than learners expect.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
    <tr><th>Position</th><th>Example</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Before the main verb</td><td>I <b>always wake up</b> at 6:30. She <b>never skips</b> breakfast.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>After the verb "be"</td><td>He <b>is usually</b> tired in the morning.</td></tr>
  </table></div>

  <div class="ccq-box">
    <h4>🔎 Check Your Understanding</h4>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Does "always" mean 100% or 50%?</b> <span>100%.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Does "never" mean 100% or 0%?</b> <span>0%.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Which happens more often: "usually" or "sometimes"?</b> <span>Usually.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>In "He is always tired", does "always" go before or after "is"?</b> <span>After — "is always".</span></div>
  </div>
</section>

