<section id="speaking">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num" style="background:var(--blue)">&#128483;</span>Speaking Practice</h2>
  <p class="section-intro">Sofia talks about her day and her family. Now you talk about yours &mdash; out loud. You only need your phone's voice memo app.</p>

  <div class="speak-card">
    <span class="speak-type">Timed monologue</span>
    <h3>One minute: my day</h3>
    <p>Set a timer for <strong>1 minute</strong>. Talk about your normal day, from morning to night: <em>"I wake up at seven. I have breakfast. I go to work at&hellip;"</em> Add how often: <em>always, usually, sometimes, never.</em></p>
    <div class="speak-how"><strong>How:</strong> Record it. Don't stop for mistakes. <strong>When you listen back, check:</strong> the frequency word sits before the verb &mdash; <em>"I usually have coffee,"</em> not <em>"I have usually coffee."</em></div>
  </div>

  <div class="speak-card">
    <span class="speak-type">Roleplay scenario</span>
    <h3>Tell me about your family</h3>
    <p><strong>Role A:</strong> Ask three simple questions: <em>"Do you have brothers or sisters? What does your mother do? What time does your family have dinner?"</em></p>
    <p><strong>Role B:</strong> Answer with full little sentences: <em>"I have one brother. He works in a shop. We have dinner at seven."</em> Then change roles.</p>
    <div class="speak-how"><strong>How:</strong> With a partner, or play both people yourself; record 2 minutes. <strong>When you listen back, check the -s:</strong> <em>he workS, she getS up.</em> It's small but important!</div>
  </div>

  <div class="speak-card">
    <span class="speak-type">Sentence challenge</span>
