<!-- 1: CONTEXT -->
<!-- SECTION: Context First: Read Before Any Rule -->
<section id="context" class="c1">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">1</span>Context First: Read Before Any Rule</h2>
  <p>Read the hobby club flyer, then the chat between Sofia and Jack. Just try to understand what they like doing. We look at the grammar after.</p>

  <div class="realia blogpost">
    <span class="doc-tag">Noticeboard Flyer</span>
    <h4>Riverside Hobby Club — Everyone Welcome!</h4>
    <p class="byline">Every week, in the community room</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Monday — Painting group, 6pm</li>
      <li>Wednesday — Guitar for beginners, 7pm</li>
      <li>Saturday — Gardening club, 10am</li>
    </ul>
    <p>New members can just come along. No experience needed!</p>
  </div>

  <div class="realia">
    <span class="doc-tag">Text Messages</span>
    <div class="chat">
      <div class="bubble left"><div class="name">Sofia</div>Hey Jack! I found a flyer for a hobby club downstairs. <span class="highlight">Do you like</span> painting or music?</div>
      <div class="bubble right"><div class="name">Jack</div>I <span class="highlight">don't really like</span> painting, but I love music! I <span class="highlight">play</span> the guitar <span class="highlight2">quite often</span>, actually.</div>
      <div class="bubble left"><div class="name">Sofia</div>Oh nice! <span class="highlight">How often do you</span> practise?</div>
      <div class="bubble right"><div class="name">Jack</div>I practise <span class="highlight2">every day</span>, but I <span class="highlight2">rarely</span> play in front of people. I'm still learning!</div>
      <div class="bubble left"><div class="name">Sofia</div>There's a beginners' guitar group on Wednesday. <span class="highlight3">Can I come</span> with you?</div>
      <div class="bubble right"><div class="name">Jack</div>Of course! <span class="highlight3">Can you bring</span> your own guitar, or do you need one?</div>
      <div class="bubble left"><div class="name">Sofia</div>I don't have one yet — <span class="highlight3">can I borrow</span> yours just for Wednesday?</div>
      <div class="bubble right"><div class="name">Jack</div>Sure, no problem! <span class="highlight">Does</span> Saturday work for gardening too? I <span class="highlight2">hardly ever</span> miss that one.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p><em>Notice:</em> Sofia and Jack ask each other lots of questions with "do" and "does". They also use words like "often", "rarely" and "hardly ever" to say how often they do things, and "can" to ask for things politely.</p>
</section>

<!-- 2: NOTICE -->
<!-- SECTION: Notice the Language (Before Any Rule) -->
<section id="notice" class="c2">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">2</span>Notice the Language (Before Any Rule)</h2>
  <p>Look again at the highlighted words. Talk to a partner about these questions.</p>
  <div class="notice-q"><b>Q1.</b> Look at "Do you like painting?" What is the first word? Where does it go — at the start, or in the middle?</div>
  <div class="notice-q"><b>Q2.</b> Now look at "Does Saturday work for gardening too?" This question is about "Saturday" (like "it"). Do we use "do" or "does" for it/he/she?</div>
  <div class="notice-q"><b>Q3.</b> Find "quite often", "rarely" and "hardly ever" in the chat. Do you think "rarely" means "a lot" or "not very much"?</div>
  <div class="notice-q"><b>Q4.</b> Look at "Can I come with you?" and "Can you bring your own guitar?" Is Sofia asking about ability (what she is able to do), or is she asking for permission/making a request?</div>
  <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--ink-soft);">Talk about your answers before you go to Section 3.</p>
</section>

<!-- 3: GRAMMAR -->
<!-- SECTION: Grammar Focus -->
<section id="grammar" class="c3">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">3</span>Grammar Focus</h2>

  <h3 style="color:var(--blue);">3.1 — Present Simple Questions</h3>
  <p>To make a question in the present simple, we put <b>do</b> or <b>does</b> at the very beginning — and the main verb loses its "-s".</p>

  <div class="tl-diagram">
    <div class="tl-diagram-title">Flip the sentence: statement → question</div>
    <svg viewBox="0 0 660 200" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
      <rect x="30" y="30" width="600" height="50" rx="10" fill="#dde6f0"/>
      <text x="330" y="61" font-size="16" fill="#2b2620" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">You <tspan font-weight="bold" fill="#4a6fa5">like</tspan> hobbies.</text>
      <text x="330" y="100" font-size="22" fill="#5c5346" text-anchor="middle">⬇</text>
      <rect x="30" y="115" width="600" height="50" rx="10" fill="#f3e0d3"/>
      <text x="330" y="146" font-size="16" fill="#2b2620" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle"><tspan font-weight="bold" fill="#c17f59">Do</tspan> you <tspan font-weight="bold" fill="#4a6fa5">like</tspan> hobbies?</text>
      <text x="330" y="185" font-size="12" fill="#5c5346" font-family="Calibri" font-style="italic" text-anchor="middle">"Do" moves to the front — the verb "like" never changes here.</text>
    </svg>
    <div class="tl-caption">For he/she/it: "She likes hobbies" → "Does she like hobbies?" — the "-s" moves from the verb onto "does", so the verb goes back to its base form.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
    <tr><th>Subject</th><th>Question form</th><th>Short answer</th></tr>
    <tr><td>I / you / we / they</td><td><b>Do</b> + subject + verb?</td><td>Yes, I do. / No, I don't.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>he / she / it</td><td><b>Does</b> + subject + verb?</td><td>Yes, she does. / No, she doesn't.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Wh- question</td><td>What / How often + do/does + subject + verb?</td><td>I play the guitar. / She practises every day.</td></tr>
  </table></div>

  <div class="error-box">
    <h4>⚠️ Don't Add "-s" Twice!</h4>
    <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
      <tr><th>❌ Incorrect</th><th>✅ Correct</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Does she likes music?</td><td><b>Does</b> she <b>like</b> music?</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Do she like painting?</td><td><b>Does</b> she like painting?</td></tr>
    </table></div>
    <p style="margin-bottom:0;">"Does" already carries the "-s" for he/she/it, so the main verb after it goes back to its base form — never "does she likes".</p>
  </div>

  <div class="ccq-box">
    <h4>🔎 Check Your Understanding</h4>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>In a question, does "do/does" go at the start or the end?</b> <span>At the start.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Do we use "do" or "does" for "she"?</b> <span>Does.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Is "Does she likes music?" correct?</b> <span>No — it should be "Does she like music?" (no -s on "like").</span></div>
  </div>

  <h3 style="color:var(--blue);">3.2 — Adverbs of Frequency (Extended)</h3>
  <p>Last week you learned always, usually, sometimes and never. Here are more frequency words, from most to least often.</p>

  <div class="tl-diagram">
    <div class="tl-diagram-title">The extended frequency scale</div>
    <svg viewBox="0 0 680 150" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
      <rect x="20" y="65" width="640" height="16" rx="8" fill="url(#freqgrad2)"/>
      <defs>
        <linearGradient id="freqgrad2" x1="0" y1="0" x2="1" y2="0">
          <stop offset="0%" stop-color="#5b4636"/>
          <stop offset="100%" stop-color="#e0d7ca"/>
        </linearGradient>
      </defs>
      <circle cx="55" cy="73" r="8" fill="#5b4636" stroke="#fff" stroke-width="2"/>
      <text x="55" y="45" font-size="12.5" fill="#5b4636" font-family="Calibri" font-weight="bold" text-anchor="middle">always</text>
      <circle cx="185" cy="73" r="8" fill="#7d5ba6" stroke="#fff" stroke-width="2"/>
      <text x="185" y="45" font-size="12.5" fill="#7d5ba6" font-family="Calibri" font-weight="bold" text-anchor="middle">usually</text>
      <circle cx="315" cy="73" r="8" fill="#4a6fa5" stroke="#fff" stroke-width="2"/>
      <text x="315" y="45" font-size="12.5" fill="#4a6fa5" font-family="Calibri" font-weight="bold" text-anchor="middle">often</text>
      <circle cx="420" cy="73" r="8" fill="#c17f59" stroke="#fff" stroke-width="2"/>
      <text x="420" y="45" font-size="12.5" fill="#c17f59" font-family="Calibri" font-weight="bold" text-anchor="middle">sometimes</text>
      <circle cx="540" cy="73" r="8" fill="#a68b3c" stroke="#fff" stroke-width="2"/>
      <text x="540" y="45" font-size="12.5" fill="#a68b3c" font-family="Calibri" font-weight="bold" text-anchor="middle">rarely</text>
      <circle cx="620" cy="73" r="8" fill="#8c8478" stroke="#fff" stroke-width="2"/>
      <text x="628" y="105" font-size="11.5" fill="#5c5346" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">hardly ever</text>
      <circle cx="660" cy="73" r="8" fill="#b0a89a" stroke="#fff" stroke-width="2"/>
      <text x="660" y="45" font-size="12.5" fill="#8c8478" font-family="Calibri" font-weight="bold" text-anchor="middle">never</text>
      <text x="340" y="130" font-size="12" fill="#5c5346" font-family="Calibri" font-style="italic" text-anchor="middle">"Rarely" and "hardly ever" mean almost the same thing — very close to "never".</text>
    </svg>
    <div class="tl-caption">New this week: often (between usually and sometimes), rarely and hardly ever (between sometimes and never).</div>
  </div>

  <p style="font-size:14px;">We also use these words to answer <b>"How often...?"</b> questions: <em>"How often do you practise?"</em> — <em>"I practise every day."</em> / <em>"I rarely practise."</em></p>

  <div class="ccq-box">
    <h4>🔎 Check Your Understanding</h4>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Is "often" more or less frequent than "sometimes"?</b> <span>More frequent.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Do "rarely" and "hardly ever" mean almost the same thing?</b> <span>Yes — both are close to "never".</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>What question do we ask to find out how frequently someone does something?</b> <span>"How often...?"</span></div>
  </div>

  <h3 style="color:var(--blue);">3.3 — Can for Requests (Review)</h3>
  <p>We use <b>can</b> to ask for something politely, or to ask permission. This is a review from before — now we use it to talk about hobbies.</p>
  <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
    <tr><th>Form</th><th>Example</th></tr>
    <tr><td><b>Can I</b> + verb...?</td><td><b>Can I</b> come with you?</td></tr>
    <tr><td><b>Can you</b> + verb...?</td><td><b>Can you</b> bring your guitar?</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Positive answer</td><td>Sure! / Of course! / No problem!</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Negative answer</td><td>Sorry, I can't. / I'm afraid not.</td></tr>
  </table></div>
  <div class="error-box">
    <h4>⚠️ No "To" After Can!</h4>
    <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
      <tr><th>❌ Incorrect</th><th>✅ Correct</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Can I to borrow your guitar?</td><td><b>Can I borrow</b> your guitar?</td></tr>
    </table></div>
  </div>

  <div class="ccq-box">
    <h4>🔎 Check Your Understanding</h4>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Is "Can I borrow your guitar?" asking about ability, or making a request?</b> <span>Making a request.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Do we add "to" after "can"?</b> <span>No — "Can I borrow", not "Can I to borrow".</span></div>
  </div>
</section>

