    <div class="vocab-card"><span class="emoji">🍳</span><div><b>cooking</b>preparing food</div></div>
    <div class="vocab-card"><span class="emoji">💃</span><div><b>dancing</b>moving your body to music</div></div>
    <div class="vocab-card"><span class="emoji">🎬</span><div><b>watching movies</b>watching films for fun</div></div>
  </div>

  <h3 style="color:var(--plum);">4.2 — Free Time Vocabulary</h3>
  <div class="collo-row">
    <span class="collo-chip">free time</span>
    <span class="collo-chip">spare time</span>
    <span class="collo-chip">weekday</span>
    <span class="collo-chip">weekend</span>
    <span class="collo-chip">to join a club</span>
    <span class="collo-chip">a beginner</span>
    <span class="collo-chip">to practise</span>
  </div>

  <h3 style="color:var(--plum);">4.3 — Likes &amp; Dislikes</h3>
  <div class="collo-row">
    <span class="collo-chip">I love...</span>
    <span class="collo-chip">I like...</span>
    <span class="collo-chip">I don't mind...</span>
    <span class="collo-chip">I don't really like...</span>
    <span class="collo-chip">I hate...</span>
  </div>
  <p style="font-size:14px;">After <b>love, like</b> and <b>hate</b>, you can use either the "-ing" form OR "to + verb" — both are correct and mean almost the same thing:</p>
  <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
    <tr><th>"-ing" form</th><th>"to + verb" form</th></tr>
    <tr><td>I love <b>painting</b>.</td><td>I love <b>to paint</b>.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>I like <b>cooking</b>.</td><td>I like <b>to cook</b>.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>He hates <b>waiting</b>.</td><td>He hates <b>to wait</b>.</td></tr>
  </table></div>
  <p style="font-size:14px;">But after <b>don't mind</b> and <b>dislike</b>, we normally only use the "-ing" form: "I don't mind <b>cooking</b>." "She dislikes <b>waiting</b>." (NOT "dislikes to wait").</p>

  <h3 style="color:var(--plum);">4.4 — More Related Vocabulary to Recognise</h3>
  <p style="font-size:14.5px;">a hobby · an activity · a member · to sign up · equipment · a beginner's group · to borrow / to lend.</p>
