<!-- SECTION: Speaking Practice -->
<section id="speaking">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num" style="background:var(--blue)">&#128483;</span>Speaking Practice</h2>
  <p class="section-intro">Hobbies are the easiest conversation in the world &mdash; everyone has them, and everyone likes talking about them. This week you do it out loud, and you ask for things politely too. Voice memo app ready!</p>

  <div class="speak-card">
    <span class="speak-type">Timed monologue</span>
    <h3>One minute: things I love (and don't)</h3>
    <p>Set a timer for <strong>1 minute</strong>. Talk about your free time with this week's pattern &mdash; <em>like / love / don't like / hate + -ing</em>: <em>"I love cooking. I like reading at night. I don't like cleaning&hellip;"</em> At least six sentences.</p>
    <div class="speak-how"><strong>How:</strong> Record without stopping. <strong>When you listen back, check the -ing:</strong> <em>"I like cooking"</em> &mdash; never <em>"I like cook."</em> Every like-verb needs its -ing partner.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="speak-card">
    <span class="speak-type">Roleplay scenario</span>
    <h3>Can you&hellip;? Sure!</h3>
    <p><strong>Role A:</strong> You are planning a hobby afternoon with a friend. Make three polite requests: <em>"Can you bring your guitar? Can you help me with the food? Can I borrow your bike?"</em></p>
    <p><strong>Role B:</strong> Answer each one &mdash; say yes to two, no to one, kindly: <em>"Sure!" / "Of course!" / "Sorry, I can't &mdash; but&hellip;"</em> Then change roles.</p>
    <div class="speak-how"><strong>How:</strong> With a partner, or both roles yourself; record 2 minutes. <strong>When you listen back, check:</strong> every request goes UP at the end &mdash; <em>"Can you help me? &#8599;"</em></div>
  </div>

  <div class="speak-card">
    <span class="speak-type">Sentence challenge</span>
    <h3>Six hobbies, one sentence each</h3>
    <p>Say one TRUE sentence with each hobby &mdash; who does it, or how often, or where. Up to <strong>60 seconds each</strong>:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><em>cooking</em></li>
      <li><em>reading</em></li>
      <li><em>cycling</em></li>
      <li><em>dancing</em></li>
      <li><em>gardening</em></li>
      <li><em>watching movies</em></li>
    </ul>
    <div class="speak-how"><strong>How:</strong> One recording, timer on. <strong>When you listen back, check:</strong> hobby words end in a soft <em>-ing</em> sound (like "sing"), not "-ink".</div>
  </div>

  <div class="tip-box">
    <h3>Tips: hobby talk opens doors</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>The best follow-up question in English is tiny: <em>"Really? How often?"</em> Learn it as one piece.</li>
      <li><em>"What do you do in your free time?"</em> &mdash; learn this question by heart. You'll use it forever.</li>
      <li>Answering "no" politely is a skill: <em>"Sorry, I can't"</em> + a reason. Practise it once in the roleplay.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>


<!-- SECTION: Listening & Watching -->
<section id="listening">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num" style="background:var(--plum)">&#127911;</span>Listening &amp; Watching</h2>
  <p class="section-intro">Hobbies and polite requests fill everyday English. Slow, clear sources &mdash; one small task each.</p>

