<!-- 3: GRAMMAR -->
<!-- SECTION: Grammar Focus -->
<section id="grammar" class="c3">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">3</span>Grammar Focus</h2>

  <h3 style="color:var(--blue);">3.1 — Countable &amp; Uncountable Nouns</h3>
  <p><b>Countable</b> nouns can be counted (one, two, three) and have a plural form. <b>Uncountable</b> nouns cannot be counted directly and have no plural form.</p>

  <div class="sort-grid">
    <div class="sort-col countable">
      <h4>Countable</h4>
      <div class="item">an egg → two eggs</div>
      <div class="item">a tomato → three tomatoes</div>
      <div class="item">an apple → four apples</div>
      <div class="item">a potato → five potatoes</div>
    </div>
    <div class="sort-col uncountable">
      <h4>Uncountable</h4>
      <div class="item">rice (NOT "a rice", NOT "two rices")</div>
      <div class="item">bread</div>
      <div class="item">water</div>
      <div class="item">pasta</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
    <tr><th>Type</th><th>Rule</th><th>Example</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Countable</td><td>a/an + singular; number + plural (-s)</td><td>an egg, three eggs</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Uncountable</td><td>no a/an; no plural; use "some" for a quantity</td><td>some rice, some water</td></tr>
  </table></div>

  <div class="ccq-box">
    <h4>🔎 Check Your Understanding</h4>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Can we say "two rices"?</b> <span>No — rice is uncountable, it has no plural.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Can we say "two eggs"?</b> <span>Yes — egg is countable.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Do we say "a water" or "some water"?</b> <span>Some water — water is uncountable.</span></div>
  </div>

  <h3 style="color:var(--blue);">3.2 — Some / Any</h3>
  <div class="tl-diagram">
    <div class="tl-diagram-title">Some or any? Follow the sentence type</div>
    <svg viewBox="0 0 660 170" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
      <rect x="20" y="55" width="180" height="60" rx="10" fill="#dde6f0"/>
      <text x="110" y="80" font-size="14" fill="#4a6fa5" font-family="Calibri" font-weight="bold" text-anchor="middle">POSITIVE</text>
      <text x="110" y="100" font-size="12.5" fill="#2b2620" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">I have some rice.</text>
      <polygon points="205,85 222,79 222,91" fill="#5c5346"/>
      <rect x="230" y="55" width="180" height="60" rx="10" fill="#f3e0d3"/>
      <text x="320" y="80" font-size="14" fill="#c17f59" font-family="Calibri" font-weight="bold" text-anchor="middle">NEGATIVE</text>
      <text x="320" y="100" font-size="12.5" fill="#2b2620" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">I don't have any bread.</text>
      <polygon points="415,85 432,79 432,91" fill="#5c5346"/>
      <rect x="440" y="55" width="200" height="60" rx="10" fill="#e8dff2"/>
      <text x="540" y="80" font-size="14" fill="#7d5ba6" font-family="Calibri" font-weight="bold" text-anchor="middle">QUESTION</text>
      <text x="540" y="100" font-size="12.5" fill="#2b2620" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">Is there any bread?</text>
      <text x="330" y="145" font-size="12" fill="#5c5346" font-family="Calibri" font-style="italic" text-anchor="middle">Exception: offers and requests use "some" — "Would you like some water?"</text>
    </svg>
    <div class="tl-caption">Some = positive sentences. Any = negative sentences and questions. But offers with "would you like...?" use "some", not "any".</div>
  </div>

  <div class="error-box">
    <h4>⚠️ Watch the Exception!</h4>
    <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
      <tr><th>❌ Sounds strange</th><th>✅ Correct</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Would you like any water?</td><td>Would you like <b>some</b> water?</td></tr>
    </table></div>
    <p style="margin-bottom:0;">When we offer something politely, we use "some" even in a question — it's a friendly exception to the rule.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="ccq-box">
    <h4>🔎 Check Your Understanding</h4>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Do we usually use "some" or "any" in negative sentences?</b> <span>Any.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Do we usually use "some" or "any" in questions?</b> <span>Any.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>What word do we use in a polite offer, like "Would you like ___ coffee?"</b> <span>Some (the exception).</span></div>
  </div>

  <h3 style="color:var(--blue);">3.3 — Possessive Adjectives (Review)</h3>
  <p>Quick review from Grade 2, Week 1 — these don't change this week, but you'll need them for talking about "my order", "your table", "our dinner".</p>
  <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
    <tr><th>I</th><th>you</th><th>he</th><th>she</th><th>we</th><th>they</th></tr>
    <tr><td>my</td><td>your</td><td>his</td><td>her</td><td>our</td><td>their</td></tr>
  </table></div>
</section>

<!-- 4: LIKE VS WOULD LIKE -->
<!-- SECTION: Like vs. Would Like — and Ordering -->
<section id="ordering" class="c4">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">4</span>Like vs. Would Like — and Ordering</h2>
  <p>These two look similar, but they mean different things.</p>
  <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
    <tr><th>Expression</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Example</th></tr>
    <tr><td><b>I like</b> + noun</td><td>A general preference (always true)</td><td>I like pasta. (in general, all the time)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><b>I'd like</b> (I would like) + noun</td><td>What you want right now (an order/request)</td><td>I'd like the spaghetti, please. (right now, at the restaurant)</td></tr>
  </table></div>

  <div class="ccq-box">
    <h4>🔎 Check Your Understanding</h4>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Does "I like pasta" mean right now, or always?</b> <span>Always — a general preference.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Does "I'd like the spaghetti" mean right now, or always?</b> <span>Right now — an order.</span></div>
  </div>

  <h3 style="color:var(--plum);">Useful Restaurant Phrases</h3>
  <div class="collo-row">
    <span class="collo-chip">What would you like?</span>
    <span class="collo-chip">I'd like...</span>
    <span class="collo-chip">Can I have...?</span>
    <span class="collo-chip">Could I have...?</span>
    <span class="collo-chip">I'll have...</span>
    <span class="collo-chip">The bill, please.</span>
  </div>
</section>

