<!-- 7: ERROR CLINIC -->
<!-- SECTION: Error Clinic -->
<section id="errorclinic" class="c7">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">7</span>Error Clinic</h2>
  <p>Read each sentence. Some have mistakes — fix them. <b>One sentence is already correct — do not "fix" it if it isn't broken.</b></p>
  <div class="box" style="padding:16px 20px;">
    <ol style="font-size:14.5px;">
      <li>"I'd like some rices, please." <button class="reveal-btn" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.style.display='block'">Reveal</button><div class="reveal-content">Incorrect — "rice" is uncountable, no plural: "I'd like <b>some rice</b>, please."</div></li>
      <li>"I have some eggs." <button class="reveal-btn" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.style.display='block'">Reveal</button><div class="reveal-content"><b>This sentence is already correct — no error here.</b> "Eggs" is countable and correctly plural after "some". Resist the urge to change anything.</div></li>
      <li>"I don't have some bread." <button class="reveal-btn" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.style.display='block'">Reveal</button><div class="reveal-content">Incorrect — negatives need "any": "I don't have <b>any</b> bread."</div></li>
      <li>"Would you like any tea?" <button class="reveal-btn" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.style.display='block'">Reveal</button><div class="reveal-content">Incorrect — offers use "some", even in a question: "Would you like <b>some</b> tea?"</div></li>
      <li>"I really like pasta." <button class="reveal-btn" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.style.display='block'">Reveal</button><div class="reveal-content"><b>Also correct.</b> This is a general preference, correctly using "like" (not "would like"). A second trap — not every sentence needs a correction.</div></li>
    </ol>
  </div>
