<!-- SECTION: Speaking Practice -->
<section id="speaking">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num" style="background:var(--blue)">&#128483;</span>Speaking Practice</h2>
  <p class="section-intro">At Pablo's housewarming, everyone talks about food: what they like, and what they would like right now. Two little words &mdash; <em>like</em> and <em>'d like</em> &mdash; and a big difference. Voice memo app ready!</p>

  <div class="speak-card">
    <span class="speak-type">Roleplay scenario</span>
    <h3>What would you like?</h3>
    <p><strong>Role A &mdash; Host (like Pablo):</strong> Offer food and drinks: <em>"Would you like some pasta? What would you like to drink?"</em></p>
    <p><strong>Role B &mdash; Guest:</strong> Answer politely &mdash; accept two things, refuse one: <em>"I'd love some, thank you!" / "Just water for me, please." / "No, thank you &mdash; I'm full!"</em> Then change roles.</p>
    <div class="speak-how"><strong>How:</strong> With a partner, or both roles yourself; record 2 minutes. <strong>When you listen back, check:</strong> <em>Would you like&hellip;?</em> = offering now; <em>Do you like&hellip;?</em> = always. Don't mix the two questions!</div>
  </div>

  <div class="speak-card">
    <span class="speak-type">Sentence challenge</span>
    <h3>Six foods, one sentence each</h3>
    <p>Say one TRUE sentence with each food &mdash; do you like it? How often do you eat it? Up to <strong>60 seconds each</strong>:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><em>rice</em></li>
      <li><em>cheese</em></li>
      <li><em>bread</em></li>
      <li><em>pasta</em></li>
      <li><em>meat</em></li>
      <li><em>sugar</em></li>
    </ul>
    <div class="speak-how"><strong>How:</strong> One recording, timer on. <strong>When you listen back, check:</strong> these foods have no plural &mdash; <em>"I eat rice,"</em> never <em>"rices."</em> And with amounts: <em>some rice, a lot of cheese.</em></div>
  </div>

  <div class="speak-card">
    <span class="speak-type">Shadowing drill</span>
    <h3>Copy the party dialogue</h3>
    <p>Choose 4 lines from this week's dialogue &mdash; two offers and two answers. Read them aloud <strong>three times</strong>:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Slowly and clearly;</li>
      <li>at normal speed;</li>
      <li>with a warm party voice &mdash; you're the host!</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="speak-how"><strong>How:</strong> Record the third time. <strong>When you listen back, check:</strong> <em>"Would you"</em> melts together in real speech &mdash; <em>"Wouldja like&hellip;?"</em> Now you'll hear it everywhere.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="tip-box">
    <h3>Tips: food talk is friend talk</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Learn the golden guest pair: <em>"I'd love some!"</em> and <em>"No, thank you &mdash; I'm full."</em> Kind yes, kind no.</li>
      <li><em>Some</em> for offers and yes-sentences, <em>any</em> for questions and no-sentences: <em>"Would you like some tea? We don't have any milk."</em></li>
      <li>Name three dishes from your country in English before the next class &mdash; you WILL be asked about them one day.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>


