<!-- SECTION: Speaking Practice -->
<section id="speaking">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num" style="background:var(--blue)">&#128483;</span>Speaking Practice</h2>
  <p class="section-intro">At the Riverside Caf&eacute;, people give instructions (<em>First, press the button&hellip;</em>) and talk about dates (<em>on the third of May</em>). This week your voice learns both. Voice memo app ready!</p>

  <div class="speak-card">
    <span class="speak-type">Give instructions</span>
    <h3>How to make my favourite drink</h3>
    <p>Think of a drink you make often &mdash; tea, coffee, anything. Explain how to make it in <strong>about 45 seconds</strong>, step by step, with imperatives and order words: <em>"First, boil the water. Then, add&hellip; Next,&hellip; Finally, enjoy!"</em></p>
    <div class="speak-how"><strong>How:</strong> Record it &mdash; even better, record it while you really make the drink. <strong>When you listen back, check:</strong> instructions start with the verb &mdash; <em>"Boil the water,"</em> not <em>"You boil."</em> And each step gets its order word.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="speak-card">
    <span class="speak-type">Dates challenge</span>
    <h3>Six dates from your life</h3>
    <p>Say six important dates aloud &mdash; with ordinal numbers, the caf&eacute; way: <em>"My birthday is on the twelfth of March."</em> Up to <strong>60 seconds each</strong>:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Your birthday</li>
      <li>A family member's birthday</li>
      <li>A holiday you love</li>
      <li>Today's date</li>
      <li>The date of your next English class</li>
      <li>One date you will never forget</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="speak-how"><strong>How:</strong> One recording, timer on. <strong>When you listen back, check the endings:</strong> <em>first, second, third, fourth&hellip; twelfth, twentieth.</em> The "-th" sound needs your tongue between your teeth!</div>
  </div>

  <div class="speak-card">
    <span class="speak-type">Shadowing drill</span>
    <h3>Copy the caf&eacute; dialogue</h3>
    <p>Choose 4 lines from this week's caf&eacute; dialogue &mdash; instructions or dates. Read them aloud <strong>three times</strong>:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Slowly and clearly;</li>
      <li>at normal speed;</li>
      <li>like a friendly barista on a busy morning.</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="speak-how"><strong>How:</strong> Record the third time. <strong>When you listen back, check:</strong> a small pause after each order word &mdash; <em>"First, | press the button."</em> The pause makes instructions easy to follow.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="tip-box">
    <h3>Tips: clear steps, clear dates</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Four order words are enough for any instructions: <em>First, Then, Next, Finally.</em> Learn them as a team.</li>
      <li>Practise dates with your own calendar: every morning, say today's date aloud. Ten seconds, real progress.</li>
      <li>The "-th" in <em>fourth, fifth</em> is hard in every language. Slow is fine &mdash; clear beats fast.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>


<!-- SECTION: Listening & Watching -->
